### User affected

@release_team

### Describe the issue

We are working on migrating the bug triage spreadsheet into a [bug-triage](https://github.com/orgs/kubernetes/projects/80/views/1) Github Project Beta. For now, we migrated it manually. 

We found that to have the project updated automatically, it seems we need to create a new Github App and then Github Action as described [here](https://docs.github.com/en/issues/trying-out-the-new-projects-experience/automating-projects#github-actions-workflows). 

Can you please help us with the following:

Update the loadwatcher library to the latest release for trimaran plugins', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/helayoty/scheduler-plugins/commits/4cbdc594cf3378922190984d360e6a276e11d87f'}, {'sha': '2b3439076c54579c3ecdacfc71ca00a23f1e42f8', 'author': {'email': 'fromani@redhat.com', 'name': 'Francesco Romani'}, 'message': 'implement strict alignment check for the noderesourcetopology filter plugin (#347)

* nrt: filter: use IsZero()

Use resource.Quantity.IsZero() helper instead of comparing
with zero quantity. This is a bit nicer to read, but most notably
saves us a relatively costly MustParse call in each function run.

No intended changes in behaviour.

Signed-off-by: Francesco Romani <fromani@redhat.com>

* nrt: filter: isolate the per-NUMA decision logic

Extract the inner logic to check if a NUMA Node is suitable
in its own function.
This change enables further cleanups, and easier changing
of the filtering logic.
It will also make adding more logs easier down the line

No intended changes in behaviour.

Signed-off-by: Francesco Romani <fromani@redhat.com>

* nrt: filter: split complex if in a sequence of ifs

Split the complex condition, to make the code easier
to read, change, and possibly add (and log) the
NUMA node reject reason in the future.

No intended change in behaviour.

Signed-off-by: Francesco Romani <fromani@redhat.com>

* nrt: filter: qos=guaranteed requires align for mem/hp

In kubernetes >= 1.23, which is already out, we can
depend on the memory manager for alignment of memory and
hugepages. So we make the alignment check consistent to
what we do for CPU.

Signed-off-by: Francesco Romani <fromani@redhat.com>

* nrt: filter: make test more extendible

Make it easier to add new test cases without intended
changes in behaviour

Signed-off-by: Francesco Romani <fromani@redhat.com>

* nrt: flter: add more test cases

Improve the test coverage of the filter plugin

#### What this PR does / why we need it:

Shorten the taint/toleration mismatch message:

Before:

```

```

Now:

```
node(s) had untolerated taint {foo: bar}
```

#### Which issue(s) this PR fixes:

Part of #108931

#### Special notes for your reviewer:

- the first commit includes the minimum changes
- ~~the second commit is a good-to-have, which unifies the message used in both scheduler and kubelet~~ (will pursue in 1.25)

#### Does this PR introduce a user-facing change?


/kind feature

/sig scheduling

#### What this PR does / why we need it:

Shorten the taint/toleration mismatch message:

Before:

```
node(s) had taint {foo: bar}, that the pod didn't tolerate
```

Now:

```
node(s) had untolerated taint {foo: bar}
```

#### Which issue(s) this PR fixes:

Part of #108931

#### Special notes for your reviewer:

- the first commit includes the minimum changes
- ~~the second commit is a good-to-have, which unifies the message used in both scheduler and kubelet~~ (will pursue in 1.25)

#### Does this PR introduce a user-facing change?


Now:

#### What this PR does / why we need it:

Some of the garbage_collector tests spawn a large number of pods (50% of the current pod capacity). Running these tests
in parallel with other tests may cause them to fail because the kubelets will be too busy spawning these pods
to finish spawning the pods needed by other tests within the time limit (1 minute).

Spawning the pods in batches might offer other tests a chance to spawn their pods within their needed timeframe, reducing the
overall flakiness of test jobs.

/kind regression

/kind flake

/sig windows
/sig testing

#### What this PR does / why we need it:

Some of the garbage_collector tests spawn a large number of pods (50% of the current pod capacity). Running these tests
in parallel with other tests may cause them to fail because the kubelets will be too busy spawning these pods
to finish spawning the pods needed by other tests within the time limit (1 minute).

Spawning the pods in batches might offer other tests a chance to spawn their pods within their needed timeframe, reducing the
overall flakiness of test jobs.

#### What type of PR is this?
/kind bug

#### What this PR does / why we need it:
This change updates the KMS envelope encryption to be able to use AES-GCM to encrypt data using the DEK instead of AES-CBC. To allow for downgrades and HA upgrades, this functionality is only used on reads.

In the next release we will be able to use AES-GCM for writes. Backwards compatibility with previously encrypted resources will be retained by falling back to AES-CBC on reads.

xref https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/81127

This PR is a rebased version of https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/86124 on master. All credits to @enj!

#### What this PR does / why we need it:

The Windows file permissions / ACLs are a bit more complex and fine-grained than the Linux file permissions. However, the Linux file permissions could be translated to some extent to Windows ACLs.

According to [1], we could translate the Linux ``user / group / other`` to the Windows SIDs ``Creator Owner ID / Creator Group ID / World``, or more precisely, ``S-1-3-0/S-1-3-1/S-1-1-0``.

As for the permissions, we can use the Generic Access Rights [3][2]: ``GENERIC_READ / GENERIC_WRITE / GENERIC_EXECUTE``.

We can use the https://github.com/hectane/go-acl library to set these permissions, which allows us to simply call ``acl.Chmod(file, mask)``, which already takes into consideration the points above.

[1] https://docs.microsoft.com/en-US/windows/security/identity-protection/access-control/security-identifiers#well-known-sids
[2] https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/secauthz/access-mask
[3] https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/secauthz/generic-access-rights

memory-backed in order to ensure they do not hit disk.

When swap is enabled, we need to ensure the content of memory-backed volumes continue to not touch disk.

* On cgroupsv2, the kubelet should set cgroupv2 controls to prevent memory-backed volumes from swapping out
* On cgroupsv1, where these controls are not available
  * document (in PRR / KEP / docs) the impact of running with swap on memory-backed volumes
  * consider not supporting swap on cgroupsv1 because of this impact?

/kind feature

it seems quiet interesting what you are working on :-)
I know Github issues are not the place for raising questions, but we are currently at the point where we see now light at the end of the tunnel :-(

99% of our applications in our clusters are Spring Boot applications. If you have worked with spring boot applications, then you know that they have a very strange behaviour in case of CPU usage. For them you can implement a limit, then the startup time increases up to multiple minutes; or you have none, in such a case the CPU usage at the beginning goes dramatically up (1-3 CPU cores) and throttles all other pods running there. After startup the CPU usage goes down to 0.1 CPU cores.

Currently this causes in our clusters when we perform automated patching and in case of parallel deployment of multiple applications a very high number of pod restarts and even failing applications already under traffic by our customers due to the high CPU utilization.

Is there a plugin, which could throttle the scheduled pods being scheduled at once based on a label and then wait for their healthiness?

Thank you in advance!
Björn

* Refactor e2e tests

This just factors out some oof the tests into test helpers that can be
re-used in new tests to be added.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

* eraser: Use fresh context for updateStatus

While testing some things I ran into issues where the context had
already timed out by the time `updateStatus` was being called.
We really want to make sure that we can send updatte the status, so use
a fresh context with its own timeout.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

* eraser: Ignore NotFound errors on remove

If remove fails with NotFound we don't need to mark the job as a failure
because what we wanted was already accomplished.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

* eraser: Change remove timeout to 5m

10s is too short for removing multiple images.
I hit timeouts when the number of images was more than just a few.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

* eraser: Add support for pruning all unused images

If the imagelist has a `*`, we'll use this as a sign to remove all
non-running images.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

* e2e: Reduce race conditions w/ running eraser pod

Seeing some flakeiness in these tests.
It is possible the flakiness is related to spinning up an eraser pod
before things that we expect to be deleted are actually deleted.
This just puts some checks in place to help ensure that doesn't happen.

> Some other questions:
> 
> * can we provide another option to test the single scheduler? (i.e., replacing the embed scheduler with the scheduler-plugins binary)
I'm not sure I get the question. We didn't add tests cases for each plugin yet, but this is the plan. If you mean to not apply the helm chart with all plugins enabled, this is possible by using the same `helm` package from `e2e framework`.
> * do you have plans to cover e2e testing for controllers?
This will be included by default when testing the plugin, as you'll apply the CRD which calls the controller as part of the flow.

This change removes the dependency on
apiservertesting testing package and leverage
the envtest framework from controller-runtime

to spin up apiserver and etcd in integration test

Using this framework will simplify the code
and remove the need for hack/testdata and
the autogen target that uses update-generated-openapi.sh
The bring up of apiserver and etcd is done in the
TestMain so that we only need to do this once and
the integration tests will not need to spin up
apiserver each time which was the case before.

As part of the this rework, ensured that all pods
are properly cleaned up and removed at the end
of each integration test.

Easier to generate new apis and to maintain less code and only one image instead of 2(scheduler and controller)

'2020-05-13T05:06:54Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-26T00:32:39Z', 'due_on': None, 'closed_at': None}, 'comments': 14, 'created_at': '2020-11-06T16:22:16Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-26T02:11:38Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '<!-- Please only use this template for submitting feature requests -->

#### What would you like to be added:

As the functionality and number of packages in `krel` continues to grow, we are starting to see divergence in how new features are implemented, tested, and maintained. We should add style guidelines and quality standards so that someone is completely new to the project can make contributions that are easily reviewed and integrated without degrading quality.

#### Why is this needed:

There are a few key areas that we have determined as important to maintain quality and consistency:

- Exposing the minimum required public API in packages (i.e. bias towards private fields in structs and interfaces)
- Follow pattern of "accepting interfaces, returning structs" (i.e [Robustness principle](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robustness_principle))
- Avoid "testing through" (i.e. make your interfaces easily mockable)
- Generate mocks in a consistent manner (we use counterfeiter)
- Establish and measure a (potentially flexible) threshold for unit test coverage
- Establish what types of features require integration / e2e testing

This is not an all-inclusive list, but can serve as a good starting point for a document that we can continually iterate on.

/assign @hasheddan @saschagrunert
